    <p>
    <br/>
    Click on the above images.
    <br/>
    <br/>
    Looking through the data using the tool we can see most tornadoes are rather short and don't last so long.
    Some do though. They have the ability to be over 2 miles wide with windspeeds up to 300 some miles per hour and travel for many miles.
    In the two images above and left we can see the widest tornado which was in May of 2004, it was 4400 yards or 2.5 miles wide.  
    In the two images above and right we can see one of the farthest traveling tornadoes at least viewed in the tool.
